Let's suppose that instead of "`#{`" and "`#}`" for push and pop, we have "`%{`" and "`%}`", just to bring the problem home for people more comfortable with C-style format strings.

Consider the following pseudocode:


```cpp
constexpr string push = "\u009b%{";
constexpr string pop  = "\u009b%}";
constexpr string red  = "\u009b91m";

string MakeRed( string s )
{
    return sprintf( "%s%s%s%s", push, red, s, pop );
}
```

It takes an input string, prepends the SGR code to turn the foreground red, and wraps it in push/pop, so now it is ready to be composed with other text, without any global knowledge of the current SGR attributes (as explained earlier in the thread).


Now let's put it to use:

```cpp
string RenderElement( Thing t, string elementName, string errorFmt )
{
    auto elementValue = t.TryGetElement( elementName );

    if( elementValue == null )
    {
        return sprintf( errorFmt, elementName );
    }
    else
    {
        return elementValue.ToString();
    }
}

Thing t = GetThing();
RenderElement( t, "foo", MakeRed( "<property not found: %s>" ) ); // Uh-oh...
```

There is a problem in the code above: the format string passed to `RenderElement` contains `%` characters: both for the `%s` (the legitimate insert) as well as in the push/pop SGR stuff (`%{`). The call to `sprintf` may get confused about what `%{` means...

Are there ways to deal with that? Yes. What are they?

1) If you have a global knowledge of how all the formatting is done, you can just put in the properly escaped format strings where necessary. That's pretty easy, **if** you have such knowledge. For my case, though, that simply can't work; the compositional nature of my scenario means that format strings can come from anywhere, including the user.

2) I could write code to parse all format strings and recognize which `%`s need to be escaped and which don't. In addition to being able to recognize relevant control sequences, it may need to have some lookahead (for example, if I need to escape "`#{`" to "`#{{`", I have to recognize if it's already been done or not). And then I have to make sure this special pre-check routine is performed everywhere before a `sprintf` is done. For libraries I own, it is doable, but not pleasant, and results in a huge amount of otherwise unnecessary string parsing.

However, there is a third option. Imagine if we simply had a different character in the control sequence, which didn't clash with the formatting character. That would make life *much* more convenient. While it would be a non-starter for an existing sequence, I don't think it's unreasonable to suggest it in this case: the control sequence is essentially brand-new, and the idea of changing it has already come up in this discussion. Hence if we have not already broached the subject with Thomas, I'd like to start that.

> Or, with your logic, would {, }, %, and each and every character that at least one programming language or standard library out there uses to denote variable substitution, be banned from escape sequences??? Hell no.

Actually, yes, I think that would be most convenient for languages / libraries that wish to write composed, SGR-colorized output to a terminal. I personally only know of `%` and `{}`; any others?

Certainly if there were a huge variety of formatting characters, it would be difficult to accomodate them all... but I don't think that's the case. We can at least accomodate languages for which people speak up, when coming up with new control sequences.

